<h2>Event in February 2019</h2>
<h3>Exceptionally warm weather throughout Europe</h3>
<br><br>
In the last days of February exceptionally high temperatures occurred throughout Europe (Figure 1), and in several countries country-wide records for February or even the entire winter (December, January, February) were observed (Figure 2).
<br><br>
In the UK, for example, temperatures in London on 26 February reached 21.2&#176;C, breaking the record for the warmest winter day. The record had already been broken the day before, when temperatures exceeded 20&#176;C during winter for the very first time. In the Netherlands in Arcen on 27 February the highest-ever country-wide winter recorded temperature of 20.5&#176;C was observed. With a minimum temperature at the same day of only -0.6&#176;C, also the daily temperature range of more than 20&#176;C was exceptionally high.
<br><br>
<br><br>
<a href="../images/feb2019/Stateofclimate_Feb2019_tx_0_25deg_day_2019_grid_ensmean_20190226_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_tx_baselayers_overlay_2019-02-26T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/feb2019/Stateofclimate_Feb2019_tx_0_25deg_day_2019_grid_ensmean_20190226_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_tx_baselayers_overlay_2019-02-26T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/feb2019/Stateofclimate_Feb2019_tx_0_25deg_day_2019_grid_ensmean_20190226_nc__2019-02-26T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/feb2019/Stateofclimate_Feb2019_tx_0_25deg_day_2019_grid_ensmean_20190226_nc__2019-02-26T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/feb2019/Stateofclimate_Feb2019_tx_0_25deg_20190226_anom_1981-2010_v19_0e_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_tx_baselayers_overlay_2019-02-26T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/feb2019/Stateofclimate_Feb2019_tx_0_25deg_20190226_anom_1981-2010_v19_0e_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_tx_baselayers_overlay_2019-02-26T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/feb2019/Stateofclimate_Feb2019_tx_0_25deg_20190226_anom_1981-2010_v19_0e_nc__2019-02-26T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/feb2019/Stateofclimate_Feb2019_tx_0_25deg_20190226_anom_1981-2010_v19_0e_nc__2019-02-26T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 1: Maximum temperature on 26 February (left) and anomaly w.r.t. 1981-2010 (right). (E-OBS)</em>
<br><br>
<br><br>
<a href="../images/feb2019/fig2_feb2019_v2.png"><img alt="" src="../images/feb2019/fig2_feb2019_v2.png" width="600px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 2. Unusually high temperatures in February 2019 in parts of Europe (orange: country record for February). Source: DWD, National Meteorological Services.</em>
<br><br>
The high temperatures were the result of a high pressure system over western Europe (Figure 3), leading to warm winds from the south and southeast and to an almost cloudless atmosphere (Figure 4) with abundant sunshine. The high temperatures enhanced the already advanced stage of nature, and increased the risk of tick bites and hay fever to higher than normal levels. Also an exceptional number of wild fires in western Europe was reported.
<br><br>
The high temperatures cannot directly be related to global warming, but global warming does increase the probability of high temperatures. In the Netherlands the highest temperatures in February are presently about 1.5&#176;C higher than a century ago. In the present climate the probability for the present record-high temperature is still very small, less than 2 percent, but a century ago this temperature would have been almost impossible.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/feb2019/fig3_feb2019.png"><img alt="" src="../images/feb2019/fig3_feb2019.png" width="400px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 3. Sea level pressure (contours) and temperature (colors) in Europe on 26 February 2019 15 UTC. Source: ECMWF/KNMI.</em>
<br><br>
<br><br>
<a href="../images/feb2019/fig4_feb2019.png"><img alt="" src="../images/feb2019/fig4_feb2019.png" width="400px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 4. Almost no clouds over western Europe on 26 February 2019 15 UTC. Source: CineSat/KNMI.</em>
<br><br>
<h2>Specific climate indicators for February 2019</h2>
High-pressure systems were dominant for the weather in large parts of Central, Eastern and Southern Europe this month, resulting in dry and relatively warm weather. The anomaly of the average temperature in February was exceptionally high in the northern and eastern part of Europe (Figure 5). Temperatures were also above average in many parts of Europe. The number of warm days (above the 90 percentile of the 1981-2010 average) was around 16 in regions of the UK (Figure 6).
<br><br>
<a href="../images/feb2019/Stateofclimate_Indices_tg_2019_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_TG_baselayers_overlay_2019-02-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/feb2019/Stateofclimate_Indices_tg_2019_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_TG_baselayers_overlay_2019-02-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
